      "name": "Hessian Matrix",
      "type": "Concept",
      "upstream_source_spans": [
        "the Hessian matrix, which describes local curvature."
      ]
    },
    {
      "mention_id": "ko_mention_dev_020",
      "lecture_id": "linear_algebra_001",
      "name": "Matrix",
      "type": "Concept",
      "upstream_source_spans": [
        "A matrix is a rectangular array of numbers that can represent a linear transformation once bases have been chosen for the input and output spaces."
      ]
    }
  ],
  "evidence_catalog": [
    {
      "evidence_id": "evidence_001",
      "lecture_id": "calculus_001",
      "span": "Let \\(f:\\mathbb{R}^n \\to \\mathbb{R}\\) be a differentiable scalar-valued function. A partial derivative measures how \\(f\\) changes when one coordinate changes while the other coordinates are held fixed. The gradient \\(\\nabla f(x)\\) collects these partial derivatives into a vector. For a unit direction \\(u\\), the directional derivative is \\(\\nabla f(x)\\cdot u\\), so the gradient points in the direction of steepest local increase. A point where the gradient is the zero vector is called a stationary point."
    },
    {
      "evidence_id": "evidence_002",
      "lecture_id": "calculus_001",
      "span": "Taylor approximation describes the local behavior of a differentiable function near a point. The first-order Taylor approximation around \\(a\\) is"
    },
    {
      "evidence_id": "evidence_003",
      "lecture_id": "calculus_001",
      "span": "\\[\nf(a+h) \\approx f(a) + \\nabla f(a)\\cdot h.\n\\]"
    },
    {
      "evidence_id": "evidence_004",
      "lecture_id": "linear_algebra_001",
      "span": "A vector space is a set of objects called vectors that can be added together and multiplied by scalars while satisfying the vector space axioms. A basis is a set of independent vectors that can represent every vector in the space through linear combinations. The number of vectors in a basis is the dimension of the vector space."
    },
    {
      "evidence_id": "evidence_005",
      "lecture_id": "linear_algebra_001",
      "span": "A matrix is a rectangular array of numbers that can represent a linear transformation once bases have been chosen for the input and output spaces. Matrix multiplication corresponds to composing linear transformations, and changing a basis changes the matrix representation without changing the underlying transformation."
    },
    {
      "evidence_id": "evidence_006",
      "lecture_id": "linear_algebra_001",
      "span": "For a square matrix \\(A\\), an eigenvector is a nonzero vector \\(v\\) whose direction is preserved by the transformation represented by \\(A\\). The corresponding eigenvalue \\(\\lambda\\) satisfies"
    },
    {
      "evidence_id": "evidence_007",
      "lecture_id": "linear_algebra_001",
      "span": "\\[\nAv = \\lambda v.\n\\]"
    }
  ]
}
